\begin_layout Standard
In this chapter, we look at unfinanced shocks to foreign prices.
 Price shocks all have elements of a negative supply shock, as increased
 prices make production more expensive.
 They also have elements of a positive demand shock as exports increase
 and imports decrease for given domestic prices.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A shock to foreign prices has the following mechanisms:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Initial shock may directly increase export competing prices
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Exports increase
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Initial shock may directly increase import prices
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Substitution away from imports tends to increase demand for domestic goods
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Higher demand prices through imported inputs can decrease domestic demand
 as well as imports
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Sign of net effects from increased import prices on demand differs for demand
 components
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Higher intermediate input prices through imported inputs
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Higher intermediate input prices have the same proporties as a negative
 shock to productivity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Higher intermediate input prices in production
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Higher unit costs in production
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Higher unit costs leads to higher output prices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Higher output prices leads to higher demand prices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Higher prices decrease demand over time
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Higher export competing prices increase domestic demand through exports
 while the domestic demand effect from increased import prices can be positive
 through reduced imports or negative through reduced private consumption
 and / or investments.
 A positive demand shock is described in the introduction and has the following
 proporties:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Increased demand leads to increased sectoral production
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Increased sectoral production leads to increased sectoral production inputs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Increased intermediate input inputs leads to increased imports and domestic
 sectoral output
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Increased capital demand leads to increased investments from imports and
 domestic sectoral output
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Increased labor demand leads to increased wages, employment and labor supply
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Increased employment and wages leads to higher household income and increased
 demand for private consumption and housing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Increased housing demand leads to increased housing prices and investments
 in housing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Increased housing prices leads to increased liquidity and demand for private
 consumption and housing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Increased production leads to higher output prices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Higher output prices leads to higher demand prices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Increased prices dampens quantity demand over time
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Full crowding out in employment
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above mechanisms are all described in further detail in the introduction.
 All shocks are unfinanced.
 All the shocks are synthetic shocks as foreign demand and interest rates
 are unchanged.
\end_layout

